  "output": "## Codebase context\n\nThis is a Python async job-scraping pipeline (httpx + SQLite), not a web frontend ‚Äî there's no React/JSX anywhere, so \"unnecessary re-renders\" doesn't apply. I found the closest equivalents: a real N+1 in the SQLite dedup layer, redundant regex recompilation in the filter, an unnecessary deep-copy in the hot path, and a sequential-pagination pattern that's ripe for concurrency. Ranked by impact:\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern ‚Äî `store.py:55-74` (`Store.diff`)\n\nEvery job gets its own `SELECT`, then its own `INSERT`/`UPDATE`. With `max_pages: 40`+ configured for Amazon/Microsoft/etc., a single run can push thousands of round trips through `sqlite3` (cursor + param marshaling overhead each time), and the touch-only path (`UPDATE last_seen`) fires once per unchanged job even though the value is identical.\n\n```python\n# now: store.py:60-72 ‚Äî one round trip per job\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    ...\n```\n\nFix ‚Äî batch the lookup, batch the touch-updates:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n\n    existing: dict[str, str] = {}\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 500):          # SQLite param cap ~999\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 500]\n        qmarks = \",\".join(\"?\" * len(chunk))\n        existing.update(\n            (r[\"key\"], r[\"content_hash\"]) for r in\n            cur.execute(f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({qmarks})\", chunk)\n        )\n\n    new, changed, touched = [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job); self._insert(cur, job, now)\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job); self._update(cur, job, now)\n        else:\n            touched.append(job.key)\n\n    if touched:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", [(now, k) for k in touched])\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nTurns O(N) selects + O(N) touch-updates into O(N/500) selects + 1 batched executemany.\n\n### 2. Redundant computation ‚Äî `filters.py:11-41`\n\n`match()` calls `_compile(include)` / `_compile(exclude)` on **every job**, recompiling the same keyword list from scratch each time. With, say, 10 keywords over 5,000 fetched listings, that's 50k+ `re.compile` calls for patterns that never change within one `filter_jobs` call.\n\n```python\n# filters.py:44-55 ‚Äî recompiles per-job inside match()\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=rules.get(\"include_keywords\"), ...)]\n```\n\nFix ‚Äî compile once outside the loop and pass patterns through:\n\n```python\ndef match(job: Job, *, include: list[re.Pattern] | None = None,\n          exclude: list[re.Pattern] | None = None, ...) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude, ...)]\n```\n\n### 3. Redundant deep-copy ‚Äî `models.py:71-75` (`Job.to_row`)\n\n```python\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    d = asdict(self)      # recursively deep-copies `raw` too\n    d.pop(\"raw\", None)    # ...then throws it away\n```\n\n`dataclasses.asdict()` deep-copies every field, including `raw` ‚Äî which for Lever/Ashby/Workday/Phenom often holds the full source payload (nested dicts, sometimes descriptions). This runs on every insert/update in `Store.diff`, i.e. for every new/changed job on every pipeline run, copying data that's discarded one line later.\n\n```python\ndef to_row(self) -> dict[str, Any]:\n    return {\n        \"key\": self.key, \"source\": self.source, \"company\": self.company,\n        \"external_id\": self.external_id, \"title\": self.title, \"url\": self.url,\n        \"location\": self.location, \"department\": self.department,\n        \"employment_type\": self.employment_type, \"posted_at\": self.posted_at,\n        \"salary_range\": self.salary_range, \"content_hash\": self.content_hash,\n    }\n```\n\n### 4. Caching/concurrency opportunity ‚Äî sequential pagination in `fetchers.py`\n\n`fetch_amazon`, `fetch_microsoft`, `fetch_workday`, `fetch_phenom`, `fetch_bytedance` all page sequentially (`for page in range(max_pages): await _get_json(...)`), even though the **first response already returns the total hit count** (`total`, `count`, `totalHits`). That's up to 40 serialized network round trips per source when the remaining pages could be fetched concurrently.\n\n```python\n# fetch_amazon, after the first page tells you `total`:\ndata0 = await _get_json(client, url, params={**base, \"offset\": 0})\ntotal = int((data0 or {}).get(\"hits\") or 0)\njobs = parse_amazon(company, (data0 or {}).get(\"jobs\") or [])\n\noffsets = range(10, min(total, max_pages * 10), 10)\npages = await asyncio.gather(*(\n    _get_json(client, url, params={**base, \"offset\": off}) for off in offsets\n))\nfor d in pages:\n    jobs.extend(parse_amazon(company, (d or {}).get(\"jobs\") or []))\n```\n\nTrade-off worth calling out: this drops the current \"stop on first page with no *new* ids\" heuristic in favor of trusting the API's `total`. Keep the existing `max_pages` cap as the safety net. For boards with thousands of roles (Amazon, Microsoft), this turns ~40 sequential round trips (seconds of latency) into a handful of parallel batches under the existing `asyncio.Semaphore(concurrency)` already used in `fetch_all`.\n\n### 5. Minor ‚Äî unbounded blocking hang risk ‚Äî `notify.py:69`\n\n```python\nwith smtplib.SMTP(host, int(os.getenv(\"SMTP_PORT\") or \"587\")) as s:\n```\n\nNo `timeout=` kwarg, so a stalled SMTP server can hang the whole run indefinitely (Python's `smtplib` default is \"no timeout\" unless passed explicitly). Given `dispatch()` runs every notifier in sequence and one hanging notifier blocks the rest, add `timeout=15` to match the `httpx` calls elsewhere in the same file.\n\n---\n\n**Not applicable to this codebase**: React re-renders (no frontend code exists ‚Äî `output/`, `templates/`, `reports/` are static/generated HTML, not a client-side framework). If there's a separate frontend repo you want reviewed, point me at it.\n",
